(1, 'Strategy & Tactics', '<p>\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	The Roman Council sent its army into Germana to wipe out rebellions there, overwhelming the poorly armed tribal warriors with archers, cavalry and a large infantry.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	Three years later, the Council decided that Germana needed a second thrashing and sent its legions back.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	But the tribes had got wise and drawn up a new strategy. They drew the archers into the woods to block their arrows. They drew the cavalry into swamps to immobilize the horses. They drew the infantry into bogs.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	Take a break: Can you think of a modern-day parallel experience?</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	Business message: The challenges faced tomorrow will not be the same ones being faced today. So do not get stuck.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<br />\r\n	David Freedman&rsquo;s CORPS BUSINESS</p>\r\n', 0, 1, 'October 11, 2012', '2012-10-11'),
(5, 'HOW TO CONTINUE RENEWING YOURSELF', '<p>\r\n	One day, a teacher went through the class of young teenagers asking each one, &ldquo;What do you want to be remembered for?&rdquo; No member of the innocent youths could give an answer. So, he chuckled and said, &ldquo;I didn&rsquo;t expect you to be able to answer it. But if you still can&rsquo;t answer it by the time you are fifty, you will have wasted your life. &ldquo;What do you want to be remembered for is a question that induces you to renew yourself, because it pushes you to see yourself as a different person &ndash; the person you can become. Continue to ask it as you go through life.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;--&nbsp;&nbsp;PETER DRUCKER - Managing the Non-Profit Organization, 1990</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	TOM ASSOCIATES Trainers&#39; Clinic holds January 16, 2013. Theme: HOW MANPOWER DEVELOPMENT MANAGERS ENGAGE STAKEHOLDERS EFFECTIVELY.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n', 0, 1, 'December 11, 2012', '2012-12-11'),
(7, 'SOME HISTORY', '<p>\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	Braille system of writing and reading for the blind was invented in 1824 by Louis Braille who, himself, had been blind since age 3.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	Between the beginning of the 19<sup>th</sup> century and end of the 20<sup>th</sup> century (about 200 years), the height of an American adult male increased by about two inches growing from about 5&rsquo;7&rdquo; tall to about 5&rsquo;9&rdquo; on the average. Gauge the gain of 2 inches in just 200 years against the millions of years man has existed on earth. Furthermore, between the beginning and close of the 20<sup>th</sup> century, the United States of America raised life expectancy of its citizens from an average of 47 years to 77 years.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	July 2, 1908 was the day Hans Wilsdorf registered the trademark ROLEX for the prestigious wrist watch.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	Bayer, the German pharmaceutical company, owned the pain killer brand name ASPIRIN but was forced to relinquish the trademark as part of Treaty of Versailles after Germany lost the first World War.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	The first cellphone was introduced in 1983 by Motorola. It was named Dyna TAC 8000x.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n', 0, 1, 'January 23, 2013', '2013-1-23'),
(8, 'TAKE A BIGGER VIEW OF YOURSELF', '<p>\r\n	The person with the most responsibility for&nbsp;your development is&nbsp;you yourself &ndash; not anyone else. And the first priority for&nbsp;your own development is to strive for excellence. Excellent workmanship is what makes such a difference in&nbsp;any person doing&nbsp;a job. Expect your job to provide stimulus only if you create the excitement, the challenge, the transformation that makes an old job enriching over and over again. Hold yourself accountable: everything flows from that. The important thing is not that you have rank, but that you have responsibility. By focusing on accountability,&nbsp;you will be able to&nbsp;take a bigger view of yourself.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;PETER DRUCKER&nbsp;1990</p>\r\n', 731, 1, 'February 11, 2013', '2013-2-11'),
(9, 'THE NIGERIAN', '<p>\r\n	<strong><u>The Nigerian</u></strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>\r\n		One in 5 Africans.</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		One in 8 Black people worldwide.</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		A Nobel Prize Winner.</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		An Olympic Gold Medallist.</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		A Grammy Award Winner.</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		A Soccer Champion.</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		A Prince of the Vatican.</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		An Oscar Nominee.</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		A Giant of Literature.</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		A Distinguished Scientist.</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		A Musical Icon.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>\r\n	Source: AFRICAN INVESTOR</p>\r\n', 668, 1, 'March 3, 2013', '2013-3-03'),
(11, 'COST MANAGEMENT', '<p>\r\n	<strong>No matter how well a business prevents cost inflation, it will still have to <em>cut costs</em>. This is because businesses are like people, and people&nbsp;can get sick no matter how carefully they exercise and control their diet. So, a time always comes when there is need for <em>cost cutting</em>. And when that time eventually comes, management usually asks, &ldquo;How can we make this operation more efficient?&rdquo; It is the wrong question. The question should be, &ldquo;Would the roof cave in if we stopped doing this operation altogether?&rdquo; And if the answer is &ldquo;Probably not&rdquo;, the operation should just get eliminated. It is always amazing how many of the things we do will never be missed. But businesses that actually succeed tremendously in cost containment don&rsquo;t wait until they have to cut costs. They build cost management into their normal operations.</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; PETER DRUCKER - Corpedia Online</strong></p>\r\n', 796, 1, 'March 12, 2013', '2013-3-12'),
(12, 'COMPETITIVE CAPABILITIES', '<p>\r\n	<strong><strong>For close to half a century, the U.S. army focused the vast majority of its planning and resources on being prepared to face the gigantic, well-equipped, highly trained and monolithic military forces of the then Soviet Union.&nbsp; But suddenly in the late 1980s, communism fell and the threat changed. Now the enemy could be any of dozens of small countries, or factions within countries, and the conflict is more likely to be a relatively constrained set of battles, or even a police action, than all-out war.</strong></strong></p>\r\n<p align="left">\r\n	<strong><strong>If a business strategy will be capability based, it will not be shaped on the assumption that it has a clearly identified set of competitors who could be expected to behave in conflict in a fairly understandable fashion. Rather, it must be one that acts faster, hits harder and is more versatile and most familiar with business complexity.</strong></strong></p>\r\n<p align="left">\r\n	<strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; David Freedman&rsquo;s <em>CORPS BUSINESS</em>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n', 669, 1, 'March 24, 2013', '2013-3-24'),
(13, 'FORTUNE FAVOURS THE BRAVE', '<p>\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong><em>&lsquo;Audaces fortuna juvat&rsquo;</em> in Latin means Fortune Favours the Brave. Fear is a smoke that holds no substance in itself, yet it chokes. And when its victim yields, it assumes the character of the Arabian jinni, a tiny smoke that grows and crystallizes into a monster and consumes the afraid. </strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>The best way to deal with fear is to have one&rsquo;s back against the wall. When man creates no room for any resort whatsoever, either the beast or the genius in man comes out. Courage is to fear what food is to hunger. Bill Crosby captures the emptiness of fear aptly: <em>&ldquo;If you are afraid, then do nothing, and be nothing.&rdquo;</em></strong><em>&nbsp;- PHARMASCOPE</em></p>\r\n', 816, 1, 'April 5, 2013', '2013-4-05'),
(14, 'CHINA - NOW THE BEAUTIFUL BRIDE', '<p>\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>In the Middle Ages, China was the preeminent nation on earth, and the most technologically advanced.</strong></p>\r\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\r\n	&sect;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>China invented paper.</strong></p>\r\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\r\n	&sect;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>China invented the printing press.</strong></p>\r\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\r\n	&sect;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>China invented the compass.</strong></p>\r\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\r\n	&sect;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>China invented the telescope.</strong></p>\r\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\r\n	&sect;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>China invented the gunpowder.</strong></p>\r\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\r\n	&sect;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>China invented the noodle, now popularly called pasta.</strong></p>\r\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\r\n	&sect;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>China already had the wheelbarrow about 1,200 years before Europe knew it.</strong></p>\r\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\r\n	&sect;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>China had used the safety matches for 2,000 years before it reached the West.</strong></p>\r\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\r\n	&sect;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>China had the blast furnace, used in making cast iron, 1,800 years before Europe knew it. </strong></p>\r\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\r\n	&sect;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>China gave the world Kung Futse (Confucius), one of the greatest philosophers that ever lived, so great he was almost deified. </strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>All these went into oblivion when China grew a culture of <em>&ldquo;Superior Race&rdquo;</em>, arrogance and profligacy. For centuries, China closed its doors to shut out the remaining world and lost industrial and economic grounds to Europe and North America.</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>Now, China is open again to the world and is simply racing back !</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>Reference: <em>Where Have All The Leaders Gone&nbsp; </em>by Lee Iacocca.</strong></p>\r\n', 626, 1, 'April 15, 2013', '2013-4-15'),
(15, 'TURNAROUND STRATEGY', '<p>\r\n	When everything about you or your business gets really complicated and overwhelming, you&rsquo;ve got to do three things.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	First, get yourself or the business out of the ditch (i.e, survival, first and foremost).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	Second, find out how you or the business got into the ditch (recognize the signs).</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	Third, make sure you do whatever it takes so you or the business don&rsquo;t go into the ditch again (put a long term plan in place).</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;ANNE MULCAHY, former CEO of Xerox.</p>\r\n', 670, 1, 'May 26, 2013', '2013-5-26'),
(16, 'A TRUE BUSINESS PLAN IDEA', '<p>\r\n	<strong>According to conventional wisdom, the first thing every business founder must do is create a business plan &ndash; a static document that describes an opportunity, its size and the problem the business can solve. The typical business plan is essentially a research exercise written at a desk before the potential business owner has even begun to build the product or service. The idea is to predict most of the unknowns of the business before putting actual investment money and other resources in it.</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>Incidentally, it is only after investing tremendous amount of resources into building and launching the product or service, after months, sometimes even years, of development that true learning comes on the venture. Sometimes the learning comes the hard way. As the boxer Mike Tyson once said about pre-fight strategies, &ldquo;Everybody has a plan until they get punched in the mouth.&rdquo; That&rsquo;s why successful new businesses are those that keep iterating, adapting from one problem to another very quickly, improving as they continually learn.</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>Only well established business executes a model; a new venture keeps looking for one.</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <em>Reference: Harvard Business Review, May 2013</em></strong></p>\r\n', 513, 1, 'June 24, 2013', '2013-6-24'),
(17, 'THE COMMON HABITS OF UNSUCESSFUL CHIEF EXECUTIVES', '<ol>\r\n	<li>\r\n		<strong>They see themselves as dominating.</strong></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li value="2">\r\n		<strong>There is no clear boundary between their personal interests and corporate interests.</strong></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li value="3">\r\n		<strong>They seem to have all the answers, often dazzling people with the speed and decisiveness with which they can deal with challenging issues.</strong></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li value="4">\r\n		<strong>They make sure that everyone is 100 percent behind them, ruthlessly eliminating anyone who might undermine their efforts.</strong></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li value="5">\r\n		<strong>They are consummate managers of their personal image in confusion with their efforts at managing and developing the corporate image.</strong></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li value="6">\r\n		<strong>They treat major obstacles as temporary impediments to be removed.</strong></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li value="7">\r\n		<strong>They often return to the strategies and tactics that made them get to the level of success they find themselves at.</strong></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>\r\n	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Reference: WHY SMART EXECUTIVES FAIL by Sydney Finkelstein</p>\r\n', 494, 1, 'July 21, 2013', '2013-7-21'),
(18, 'RELENTLESS SUCCESS', '<p>\r\n	<strong>You want to enjoy a relentless success in what you do? You must have an idea and that idea you will begin with a LAUNCH process. You will have to see an opportunity behind which you can put in personal as well as other accessible resources to capitalize on that idea of yours. This stage demands that you must be comfortable with experimentation and iteration.</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>Then you advance to the next success phase, which is RUMP UP. This is the phase where you bring your idea to scale. You will mobilise the appropriate resources at the right time and in right standards so as to deliver on the promise of the idea.</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>If you are fortunate, you just glide into the EXPLOITATION phase of your idea. You capture share, you capture profits. But then, other people now notice you well and start to try your idea and compete with you. If your advantage will not be watered down, you will have to heighten your efficiency, but also start thinking of moving to the next phase.</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>That next phase is RECONFIGURATION. This phase requires that you are not afraid to radically rethink your initial idea and mobilize new resources. You forge ahead or, even, consider a DISENGAGEMENT process by which you move into the next generation ideas. To do this, however, you really will be a tough-minded innovator.</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; (<em>Havard Business Review</em>)</strong></p>\r\n', 492, 1, 'July 31, 2013', '2013-7-31'),
(19, 'WHAT DO YOUR FEARS LOOK LIKE?', '<p>\r\n	<strong><span style="font-size: 11pt;">What do your fears look like? What pictures, words, or objects would you use to capture your fears?</span></strong><span style="font-size: 11pt;"><o:p></o:p></span></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong><span style="font-size: 11pt;">A construction worker gets busy on a skyscraper. One fellow watches him work sixty meters (about 200 feet) above the ground on the scaffolding arrayed around the outside of the twenty four-storey skyscraper. This fellow feels a nervousness that is making him numb while standing on the ground &ndash; never mind thinking of climbing up to the construction worker.</span></strong><span style="font-size: 11pt;"><o:p></o:p></span></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong><span style="font-size: 11pt;">When the worker gets to the ground the fellow asks him whether he ever experiences that queasy dizziness that accompanies fear of heights, even for a moment. &ldquo;If I had, I wouldn&rsquo;t be here in one piece now,&rdquo; the skyscraper worker replies curtly, &ldquo;In fact, I&rsquo;d be dead. For me, that kind of fear would be unreasonable, and unhealthy.&quot;</span></strong><span style="font-size: 11pt;"><o:p></o:p></span></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong><span style="font-size: 11pt;">Now, just think about the influence of fear on the life of many people &ndash; how it inhibits creativity and infect self-confidence. But contained, fear is incapable of harming or controlling anyone: it stays controlled.</span></strong><span style="font-size: 11pt;"><o:p></o:p></span></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong><span style="font-size: 11pt;">Failure to attain a goal, failure to realize a dream, unemployment, business failure, homelessness, poor health, dying and heading for &lsquo;hell&rsquo; &ndash; people contemplate such calamity all the time, however remote the possibility they will fall victim of these things. People simply harbour and feed the fear.&nbsp;</span></strong><span style="font-size: 11pt;"><o:p></o:p></span></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong><span style="font-size: 11pt;">Think about how fear affects your performance. Fear paralyzes some people &ndash; not only can&rsquo;t they perform at their best, they become unable to perform at all. However, just check it out: the nervousness speakers &ndash; and</span></strong><span class="apple-converted-space"><b><span style="font-size: 11pt;">&nbsp;</span></b></span><em><b><span style="font-size: 11pt;">all speakers</span></b></em><strong><span style="font-size: 11pt;">&nbsp;to be sure &ndash; feel before a public speaking engagement. It is a nervousness that does not need to paralyze them. Rather, experienced speakers use it as an energizer. It turns out to give a blast of adrenaline that translates into an extra jolt of excitement in their speeches. It&rsquo;s true for runners, footballers, and other sports champions too, just as it is for business people poised on the starting blocks. The jitters they experience add to their explosive leap towards their goal.</span></strong><span style="font-size: 11pt;"><o:p></o:p></span></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong><span style="font-size: 11pt;">Fear converted to energy drives us courageously forward, straight towards the thing we&rsquo;re afraid of. It can help in dealing with reality rather than avoiding it.</span></strong><span style="font-size: 11pt;"><o:p></o:p></span></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong><span style="font-size: 11pt;">&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;</span></strong><em><b><span style="font-size: 11pt;">Adapted from</span></b></em><strong><span style="font-size: 11pt;">&nbsp;THINK LIKE A GENIUS by Todd Siler</span></strong><span style="font-size: 11pt;"><o:p></o:p></span></p>\r\n', 444, 1, 'August 14, 2013', '2013-8-14'),
(20, 'A MESSAGE FROM INDIA', '<p>\r\n	<strong>Over the last two decades, India has become a global hub for software development and offshoring of innovative back-office services. However, Indian institutes and educational systems, with a few exceptions, remain incapable of producing talents in the quality needed to keep these innovation specialties going. So companies that need the talents are developing their own innovative ways to overcome this.</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>Take IBM as an example. IBM has been known for the last 100 years to be one of the most innovative companies in the world. India&rsquo;s institutional shortcomings notwithstanding, here is the headcount profile of IBM&nbsp;</strong><strong>employees</strong><strong>:</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<u>2003</u>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <u>2010</u>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <u>2012</u></strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>Worldwide&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 310,000&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 400,000&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 433,000</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>USA-based&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 135,000&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 105,000&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; 98,000</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>India-based&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;9,000&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; 75,000&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 150,000</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>Other countries&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 166,000&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 220,000&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 185,000</strong></p>\r\n<p style="margin-left:1.5in;">\r\n	<strong>Source:&nbsp; Nirmalya Kumar on TED Talks.</strong></p>\r\n', 520, 1, 'September 4, 2013', '2013-9-04'),
(21, 'YOUR EYE ON THE BALL', '<p align="center">\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>The laser is one source from which Tom Associates Training learnt its business lesson.</strong></p>\r\n<div>\r\n	<strong>Let&rsquo;s start from the sun, a powerful source of energy. Every hour the sun washes the earth with billions of kilowatts of energy. Yet with just a little shade you may even bathe in the light of the sun for hours at a time with few ill effects.</strong></div>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>A laser is a weak source of energy. A laser takes a few watts of energy and focuses them in a coherent stream of light. But with a laser you can drill a hole in a diamond.</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>When you focus yourself or your business, you create the same effect. You create a powerful, laser-like ability to dominate your environment or a market. That&rsquo;s a focusing lesson Tom Associates Training is talking about.</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>When you or your business become unfocused, you lose your power. You become a sun that dissipates its energy over too many things and too many markets.</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>Are companies focusing themselves to develop the power of a laser or are they trying to outshine the sun?</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>When you spread energy or resources thinly, you reach a point of diminishing returns, you lose your efficiency, your competitiveness. You become a red giant, a burned-out hulk of a star hundreds of times larger than the sun, but with a surface temperature half as hot. An ability to manage a diverse collection of unrelated businesses and services is ever suspect.</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>Fortunately some chief executives of business organizations have already gotten the message. They are getting back to basics. They are learning the lesson of the laser &ndash; how to focus.</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>And so should you. The future of your all you do depends on it.</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Reference: FOCUS by Al Ries</strong></p>\r\n', 576, 1, 'September 19, 2013', '2013-9-19'),
(22, 'NATION BUILDING', '<p align="left">\r\n	<strong><span style="font-size: 12px;">Where kings still rule, the prosperity of the people depends in large part on the quality of the kings.&nbsp; If they have a good king, then they probably will have a good kingdom. If the king is a wise leader, then his kingdom probably prospers as a result.</span></strong></p>\r\n<p align="left">\r\n	<strong><span style="font-size: 12px;">In comparison, building a nation should be different. Not the greatness or wisdom of one. Not the </span><em style="font-size: 12px;">&ldquo;it all depends on me&rdquo;</em><span style="font-size: 12px;">. Rather, nation building answers to some critical questions for building a great and prosperous one. The questions are:</span></strong></p>\r\n<p align="left">\r\n	<strong><span style="font-size: 12px;">&sect;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; What </span><em style="font-size: 12px;">processes</em><span style="font-size: 12px;"> must be created that will give the nation good leadership for thousand years in the future?</span></strong></p>\r\n<p align="left">\r\n	<strong><span style="font-size: 12px;">&sect;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; What defines the endurance of the nation to build?</span></strong></p>\r\n<p align="left">\r\n	<strong><span style="font-size: 12px;">&sect;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; On what values to build the nation?</span></strong></p>\r\n<p align="left">\r\n	<strong><span style="font-size: 12px;">&sect;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; What guidelines and mechanisms to construct to bring up the kind of nation envisioned?</span></strong></p>\r\n<p align="left">\r\n	<strong><span style="font-size: 12px;">Nation building is anchored on creating a constitution and laws to which all present and future leaders will be subservient, a constitution and laws that are based on human ideals and values.</span></strong></p>\r\n<p align="left">\r\n	<strong><span style="font-size: 12px;">&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Reference: </span><em style="font-size: 12px;">Built to Last </em><span style="font-size: 12px;">by James C. Collins and Jerry I. Porras</span></strong></p>\r\n', 425, 1, 'November 8, 2013', '2013-11-08'),
(23, 'THINK DEEPLY: WHAT ARE YOUR VALUES?', '<p>\r\n	<strong>It is very rare to find a conflict between a person&rsquo;s strengths and the way that person performs. Strength and performance are complementary. But it is common to find a conflict between what a person values and that same person&rsquo;s strength. What one does well &ndash; even very well &ndash; and successfully may not fit with what one truly values in life.</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong style="font-size: 12px;">For a country, resource potentials and developmental performance should be complementary. It is unfortunate, however, that we do find conflicts between the sense of values paraded by peoples of a country and that same country&rsquo;s resources and potentials. The use to which citizens of the country put their resources may not fit with what they profess as their values in life.</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong style="font-size: 12px;">Values are and should be the ultimate test.</strong><strong style="font-size: 12px;">&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\r\n	<strong>See <em>Management Challenges for the 21<sup>st</sup> Century</em>, by Peter Drucker.</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>SUBSCRIBE TO NEWSLETTERS.</strong></p>\r\n', 452, 1, 'January 5, 2014', '2014-1-05'),
(24, 'FIRST TIMELY ADVICE TO FUTURE LEADERS', '<p>\r\n	<strong>Have you read the book&nbsp;<em>Rules of Work</em> by Richard Templar? Beautiful advise to you if you are a serious Future Leader. There are ten of them, and here are the first two:</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong style="font-size: 12px;"><u>RULE ONE</u>- WALK YOUR TALK</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong style="font-size: 12px;">*&nbsp; Get Your Work Noticed -&nbsp;</strong><strong style="font-size: 12px;">The unsolicited report is a brilliant way to stand out from the crowd.</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong style="font-size: 12px;">* &nbsp;Never Stand Still -&nbsp;</strong><strong style="font-size: 12px;">In an ideal world the rules player will have got their work done by the lunch time, so that they have the afternoon free.</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong style="font-size: 12px;">*&nbsp; Volunteer Carefully -&nbsp;</strong><strong style="font-size: 12px;">Before you put up your hand to volunteer for anything, think very carefully.</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong style="font-size: 12px;">*&nbsp; Carve Out a Niche for Yourself -&nbsp;</strong><strong style="font-size: 12px;">If the other bosses think you are a good idea, then your boss really has to go along with it.</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong style="font-size: 12px;">*&nbsp; Know Something Others Don&rsquo;t -&nbsp;</strong><strong style="font-size: 12px;">Whatever it is, make sure it is relevant, topical and interesting.</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong style="font-size: 12px;">*&nbsp; Be 100% Committed -&nbsp;</strong><strong style="font-size: 12px;">You are going to be vigilant, dedicated, watchful, keen, ready, prepared, cautious, alert and &#39;on the ball&#39;.</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong style="font-size: 12px;">*&nbsp; Enjoy What You Are Doing -&nbsp;</strong><strong style="font-size: 12px;">There is no shame in saying you enjoy your work.</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong style="font-size: 12px;">*&nbsp; Develop the Right Attitude -&nbsp;</strong><strong style="font-size: 12px;">Side with management and Always l</strong><strong style="font-size: 12px;">ook out for &#39;No. 1&#39;.</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong style="font-size: 12px;">*&nbsp; Never Let Anyone Know How Hard You Work -&nbsp;</strong><strong style="font-size: 12px;">Never ask for an extension of time;&nbsp;</strong><strong style="font-size: 12px;">Never moan or complain, but yet&nbsp;</strong><strong style="font-size: 12px;">Be assertive not to get overloaded.</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong style="font-size: 12px;"><u>RULE TWO</u> &ndash; KNOW THAT YOU&rsquo;RE BEING JUDGED AT ALL TIMES</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong style="font-size: 12px;">*&nbsp; Dress Well.</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong style="font-size: 12px;">*&nbsp; Cultivate a Smile.</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong style="font-size: 12px;">*&nbsp; No Limp Fish &ndash; Develop a Perfect Handshake.</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong style="font-size: 12px;">*&nbsp; Exude Confidence and Energy -&nbsp;</strong><strong style="font-size: 12px;">When you walk through the office first thing in the morning, there should be a spring to your step.</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong style="font-size: 12px;">*&nbsp; Develop a Style that Gets You Noticed.</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong style="font-size: 12px;">*&nbsp; Pay Attention to Personal Grooming -&nbsp;</strong><strong style="font-size: 12px;">Make each day as conscientious as an interview day.</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong style="font-size: 12px;">*&nbsp; Be Attractive -&nbsp;</strong><strong style="font-size: 12px;">Never slouch, slump or be scruffy</strong><strong style="font-size: 12px;">.</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong style="font-size: 12px;">*&nbsp; Be Cool -&nbsp;</strong><strong style="font-size: 12px;">Remain sophisticated at all times.</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong style="font-size: 12px;">*&nbsp; Speak Well -&nbsp;</strong><strong style="font-size: 12px;">Be bright, clear, pleasant and simple.</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong style="font-size: 12px;">*&nbsp; Write Well -&nbsp;</strong><strong style="font-size: 12px;">How you write for others to read is of utmost and crucial importance.</strong></p>\r\n', 566, 1, 'February 5, 2014', '2014-2-05'),
(25, 'SECOND TIMELY ADVICE TO FUTURE LEADERS', '<p>\r\n	<strong>Have you read <em>Rules of Work</em> by Richard Templar? Beautiful advise to you if you are a serious Future Leader. There are ten of them, and we already presented the first two. Here are the next two:</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong style="font-size: 12px;"><u>RULE THREE</u> &ndash; HAVE A PLAN</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>\r\n		<strong style="font-size: 12px;">Know What You Want Long Term</strong></li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		<strong>You have to have an end game &ndash; a dream</strong></li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		<strong style="font-size: 12px;">Know What You Want Short Term</strong></li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		<strong>Deadlines, prioritized tasks, basic routines</strong></li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		<strong style="font-size: 12px;">Study Promotion System</strong></li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		<strong>Look upwards to the most senior position possible</strong></li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		<strong>Look at the lowest</strong></li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		<strong>Plot all the steps in between</strong></li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		<strong>Mark your own place</strong></li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		<strong>List the steps needed to get to the most senior possible</strong></li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		<strong>Develop a Game Plan </strong></li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		<strong style="font-size: 12px;">Set Objectives</strong></li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		<strong>It is almost impossible to be successful if you don&rsquo;t set objectives</strong></li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		<strong style="font-size: 12px;">Know Your Role</strong></li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		<strong>Your role is how you fit into the team</strong></li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		<strong style="font-size: 12px;">Know Your Strengths and Weaknesses</strong></li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		<strong style="font-size: 12px;">Identify Key Times and Events</strong></li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		<strong>There is no point using all your energy and power when it isn&rsquo;t necessary</strong></li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		<strong style="font-size: 12px;">Anticipate Threats</strong></li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		<strong>Each threat that becomes a reality is an opportunity to grow and change</strong></li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		<strong style="font-size: 12px;">Look for opportunities and l<strong>earn to see opportunities as balls &ndash; if they get thrown your way, you have but a split second to catch them.</strong></strong></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong style="font-size: 12px;"><u>RULE FOUR</u> &ndash; IF YOU CAN&rsquo;T SAY ANYTHING NICE, SHUT UP</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>\r\n		<strong style="font-size: 12px;">Don&rsquo;t Gossip.&nbsp;</strong><strong style="font-size: 12px;">There is one part of this rule which is really, really simple: don&rsquo;t pass anything on</strong></li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		<strong style="font-size: 12px;">Don&rsquo;t Bitch</strong></li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		<strong>Moaning is pointless. It is unproductive and achieves nothing</strong></li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		<strong style="font-size: 12px;">Compliment People Sincerely</strong></li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		<strong style="font-size: 12px;">Be Cheerful and Positive</strong></li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		<strong style="font-size: 12px;">Ask Question</strong></li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		<strong style="font-size: 12px;">Use &ldquo;Please&rdquo; and &ldquo;Thank You&rdquo; a lot</strong></li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		<strong style="font-size: 12px;">Don&rsquo;t Swear.&nbsp;</strong><strong style="font-size: 12px;">You may say anything you want at home, or in the car on your own. But at work, you don&rsquo;t swear</strong></li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		<strong style="font-size: 12px;">Be a Good Listener&nbsp;</strong><strong style="font-size: 12px;">Good listening is a skill, a special talent that you will have to practice and learn</strong></li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		<strong style="font-size: 12px;">Only Speak Sense.&nbsp;</strong><strong style="font-size: 12px;">There are times when all the hard work can be devastated, destroyed, by a careless word or unguarded moment.</strong></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>\r\n	<span style="font-size: 12px;">LIKE US ON FACEBOOK</span></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<span style="font-size: 12px;">WOULD YOU LIKE TO RECEIVE OUR REGULAR NEWSLETTERS? SEND US YOUR EMAIL ADDRESS..&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n', 522, 1, 'March 16, 2014', '2014-3-16'),
(26, 'THIRD TIMELY ADVICE TO FUTURE LEADERS', '<p>\r\n	<strong>The book <em>Rules of Work</em> by Richard Templar has beautiful advise for you if you are a serious Future Leader. There are ten of them, and we already presented the first four. Here are the next two:</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong style="font-size: 12px;"><u>RULE FIVE</u> &ndash; LOOK AFTER YOURSELF</strong></p>\r\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\r\n	v&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>Know the ethics of your industry or government.</strong></p>\r\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\r\n	v&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>Know the legalities of your industry or governance.</strong></p>\r\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\r\n	v&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>Set personal standards - you must endeavour to be the very best you can at all times.</strong></p>\r\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\r\n	v&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>Never lie - you are allowed to talk up your qualities or skills or expertise; just don&rsquo;t actually tell a lie.</strong></p>\r\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\r\n	v&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>Never cover up lies for anyone else.</strong></p>\r\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\r\n	v&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>Keep records.</strong></p>\r\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\r\n	v&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>Know the difference between the Truth and the Whole Truth.</strong></p>\r\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\r\n	v&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>Cultivate your support/contacts/friends.</strong></p>\r\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\r\n	v&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>Understand other persons&rsquo; motives - anybody whose motives show up to be Needs and Fear and Greed should be treated carefully.</strong></p>\r\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\r\n	v&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>Assume everyone else is playing by different rules - the rule book you now have must remain a secret. If you reveal your rules you have broken the rules.</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong style="font-size: 12px;"><u>RULE SIX</u> &ndash; BLEND IN</strong></p>\r\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\r\n	v&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>Know the Corporate Culture - you don&rsquo;t have to buy into the corporate culture (you don&rsquo;t have to believe in it); all you have to do is fit in.</strong></p>\r\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\r\n	v&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>Speak the Language - if they all use geeky language, then you too must use it.</strong></p>\r\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\r\n	v&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>Be adaptable in your dealings with different people</strong></p>\r\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\r\n	v&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>Know where to hang out and when - get your face known, get your name known.</strong></p>\r\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\r\n	v&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>Understand the Social Protocol.</strong></p>\r\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\r\n	v&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>Know the rules about Authority &ndash; you may be working where the real power resides in the hands of a consultant, a secretary, a junior manager.</strong></p>\r\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\r\n	v&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>Know the rules about Office Hierarchy - Office protocols and hierarchies are old fashioned, petty, small minded, outdated and yet still very much with us.</strong></p>\r\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\r\n	v&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>Never disapprove of others.</strong></p>\r\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\r\n	v&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>Understand the |Herd Mentality - never clone or lose all sense of your individuality even while blending in.</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong style="font-size: 12px;">LIKE US ON FACEBOOK</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong style="font-size: 12px;">WOULD YOU LIKE TO RECEIVE OUR REGULAR NEWSLETTERS? SEND US YOUR EMAIL ADDRESS.&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n', 395, 1, 'May 8, 2014', '2014-5-08'),
(27, 'FOURTH TIMELY ADVICE TO FUTURE LEADERS', '<p>\r\n	<strong>Here are the next two of the ten</strong>&nbsp;<em><strong>Rules of Work</strong></em>&nbsp;<strong>by Richard Templar. We already serialised the first six.</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong><u>RULE SEVEN</u> &ndash; ACT ONE STEP AHEAD</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>\r\n		<strong>Dress One Step Ahead</strong></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\r\n	<strong>&nbsp; You may choose what job you want, you must also choose to dress like that job demands. Then you will get or retain that job.</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>\r\n		<strong>Talk One Step Ahead</strong></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\r\n	<strong>&nbsp; Be focused and dynamic, keep personal details to yourself. Bosses and bosses-in-waiting don&rsquo;t chatter or gossip about their social lives.</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>\r\n		<strong>Act One Step Ahead</strong></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\r\n	<strong>&nbsp; Carrying out the rules requires strength of character, willpower, determination, honesty, courage, experience, great talent, dedication, &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;drive, nerve and charisma.</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>\r\n		<strong>Think One Step Ahead</strong></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;You will start to think like a boss and less like a worker.</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>\r\n		<strong>Address Corporate Issues and Problems</strong></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\r\n	<strong>&nbsp; If the company suggests a new procedure, immediately think how it affects your customers and not you first.</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>\r\n		<strong>Talk of &lsquo;We&rsquo; Rather than &lsquo;I&rsquo;</strong></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\r\n	<strong>&nbsp; If you go to meetings it is so much more grown up (and &lsquo;cool&rsquo;) to talk of We instead of I.</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>\r\n		<strong>Walk the Talk</strong></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;You&rsquo;ve got to become whoever and whatever it is you aspire to be.</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>\r\n		<strong>Spend More Time with Senior Staff.</strong></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>\r\n		<strong>Get People to Assume You Have Already Made the Step </strong></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\r\n	<strong>&nbsp; Make people aware that you know the job; are experienced; are serious; are reliable and responsible; are trustworthy.</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>\r\n		<strong>Prepare for the Step After Next.</strong></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong><u>RULE EIGHT</u> - CULTIVATE DIPLOMACY</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>\r\n		<strong>Ask Questions More in Times of Conflict.</strong></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>\r\n		<strong>Don&rsquo;t Take Sides</strong></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\r\n	<strong>&nbsp; Stay on the fence whatever you do, because if you don&rsquo;t, then one side will blame you as well as the person they were originally arguing &nbsp; &nbsp;with.</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>\r\n		<strong>Know When to Keep Your Opinion to Yourself</strong></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; The real reason for expressing an opinion is because you have been asked to.</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>\r\n		<strong>Be Conciliatory.</strong></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>\r\n		<strong>Be Adept at Holding Your Temper.</strong></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>\r\n		<strong>Never Get Personal</strong></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\r\n	<strong>&nbsp; Getting personal can ultimately get you sacked at worst and lose you respect and friends at best.</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>\r\n		<strong>Know How to Handle Other People&rsquo;s Anger</strong></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\r\n	<strong>&nbsp; Just leave. That&rsquo;s it. Say nothing, just walk out. Do this often enough and they get the message.</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>\r\n		<strong>Stand Your Ground</strong></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\r\n	<strong>&nbsp; Adopt the broken record technique: &ldquo;I don&rsquo;t appreciate being treated like this.&rdquo; Say this time without end, but don&rsquo;t lose your temper or they &nbsp; may feel they have &lsquo;won&rsquo;.</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>\r\n		<strong>Be Objective</strong></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; However, before you react, think of the long-term plan.</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>\r\n		<strong>Put Things in Perspective</strong></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p style="margin-left:.5in;">\r\n	<strong>&nbsp; You have to learn to switch off, relax, not take it so seriously, enjoy it more, put things into perspective.</strong></p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<strong style="font-size: 12px;">LIKE US ON FACEBOOK</strong></p>\r\n', 462, 1, 'May 28, 2014', '2014-5-28');
