(37, 'BUDGETING AND BUDGETARY CONTROL', '<p>\r\n	The programme is designed to equip Managers and Heads of Departments with knowledge and skills necessary to enable them effectively manage and monitor the budgets implementation on a day-to-day basis. This course also equips managers with the skills they need to put in place corrective budgetary actions. Managers who go through this course are better positioned to deliver on their budgets - own their budgets, explain variances when they occur and take remedial actions in good time.<br />\r\n	<br />\r\n	DAY ONE<br />\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;What is a budget?<br />\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;Why Budget?<br />\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;The main characteristics of budgeting<br />\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;Types of budget<br />\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;Outline of the budgetary process<br />\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;Budget preparation with a typical practical illustration of a budget<br />\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;Implementing the budget &ndash; key success factors<br />\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;Benchmarking for performance management<br />\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;Advantages of budgets to a business organizations</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	DAY TWO<br />\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;What is budgetary control?<br />\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;Its significance<br />\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;What are the steps for installing an effective system of budgetary control<br />\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;Management action and cost control<br />\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;Organization for budgeting<br />\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;Importance of budgetary control in project management<br />\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;Applicability of budget and budgetary control:<br />\r\n	1&nbsp;Measuring performance<br />\r\n	2&nbsp;Analyzing budget variances<br />\r\n	3&nbsp;Actions to take after analysis</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	DAY THREE<br />\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;Alternative budgeting methods<br />\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;Budget organization and administration<br />\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;Within the context of budgetary control: explain specific roles of planning, motivation and evaluation<br />\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;How those roles may conflict with 