(40, 'BUSINESS AND PERSONAL FINANCIAL STRATEGY (FINANCE FOR NON-FINANCE MANAGERS)', '<p>\r\n	Exposure of managers to important financial concepts in day-to-day business transactions. It will help them take better decisions on the basis of financial implications on the business and, by extension, on their personal lives. It will also make managers know how to strengthen the internal control mechanisms for the organization, just as it helps them to take better control of their financial fortunes.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	Broad Competencies Addressed<br />\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;Awareness, understanding and interpretation of the company&rsquo;s Accounting and Financial statements.<br />\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;Effectiveness on the use of finance and accounting information.<br />\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;Ability to process and screen financial transactions.<br />\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;Comfortable decisions based on Accounting and Financial information.<br />\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;Ability to manage company performance strategically.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<br />\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	DAY ONE<br />\r\n	What Accounting Is.<br />\r\n	An Understanding of the Income Statement<br />\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;Revenue<br />\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;Cost<br />\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;Gross surplus<br />\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;Expenses<br />\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;Overheads.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	An Understanding of the Balance Sheet<br />\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;The funding side<br />\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;The investment side<br />\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;The use to put a balance sheet.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	DAY TWO<br />\r\n	Common Size Ratio (CSR)<br />\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;Compare the performance during one period with another. (Use the income statement for two or more years)<br />\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;Compare the percentages for each item with the overall relationships for each year<br />\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;Note the deviations from the budget<br />\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;Note all fluctuations in relationships<br />\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;Ascertain reasons for deviations and fluctuations in relationships<br />\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;Prepare action plan to improve the situation.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	Cash Flow and Its Projection<br />\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;Generating enough cash to meet obligations<br />\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;Cash outflows to match cash inflows<br />\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;When cash flow deficiencies are found<br />\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;When excess cash is revealed.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	DAY THREE<br />\r\n	Accounting Ratios<br />\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;Liquidity Ratios.<br />\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;Current ratios<br />\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;Acid ratio<br />\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;Current assets and liabilities<br />\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;Improving liquidity ratios.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	Petty Cash Management<br />\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;Tracking small cash expenses<br />\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;The float or imprest<br />\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;Petty Cash Book and its entries<br />\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;Minimising fraud.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	DAY FOUR<br />\r\n	Bank Reconciliation<br />\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;How bank statements often vary from cash book balances<br />\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;Unpresented cheques<br />\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;Uncredited cheques<br />\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;Errors and omissions.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	Interpretations for Management Effectiveness:<br />\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;Judiciously spend and account for entrusted funds<br />\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;Generate reports on simple financial dealings<br />\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;Follow guidelines and due process in handling business funds<br />\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;Understand basic Books of Accounts to enhance accountability<br />\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;Identify and check fraud through internal control procedures<br />\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;Read the progress of the company to develop the right strategies.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;Taxation<br />\r\n	-&nbsp;Principles of taxation<br />\r\n	-&nbsp;What tax means<br />\r\n	-&nbsp;Types of taxes<br />\r\n	-&nbsp;Incidence of&nbsp; tax<br />\r\n	-&nbsp;Tax Avoidance and Evasion<br />\r\n	-&nbsp;Who benefits from tax<br />\r\n	-&nbsp;Tax Planning.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	DAY FIVE<br />\r\n	Personal Financial Planning<br />\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;A Parable of