(66, 'KEY ACCOUNT MANAGEMENT', '<p>\r\n	This Key Account Management Course teaches participants the relevant marketing, selling and relational skills needed today to grow and keep an Account for life. Every forward looking company sees its Key Accounts as &ldquo;tangible external assets&rdquo; and &ldquo;partners for profit&rdquo; to the Company. For your assets to continue to yield maximally, it must be effectively and efficiently managed. If indeed &ldquo;80%&rdquo; of our current business comes from &ldquo;20%&rdquo; of our Key Accounts (or such disproportionate relationships), they need to be strategically managed. If losing an account is very &ldquo;painful&rdquo;, that account must be a key account. We must therefore manage the account like an Asset.<br />\r\n	Key Account Managers should ever be so vigilant not to &ldquo;supply ammunitions to competitors&rdquo;.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	<br />\r\n	DAY ONE<br />\r\n	Basic Principles&nbsp; of Key Account Management<br />\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;Beyond muddling through<br />\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;Strategic business profile requiring executive support<br />\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;Positioning<br />\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;Work Teams<br />\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;Customer Involvement<br />\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;Long term orientation</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	Challenges of Markets<br />\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;Customer power<br />\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;Supplier power<br />\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;Market maturity<br />\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;Globalisation<br />\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;Customer Retention<br />\r\n	Cautions for Key Account Management<br />\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;Too many eggs in one basket<br />\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;Insufficient benefits to the distributor<br />\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;Insufficient benefits to the potential key account<br />\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;Limitation of opportunities<br />\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;Cost and Bureaucracy<br />\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;Significant organizational change<br />\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	Levels of Business Relationship<br />\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;Exploratory<br />\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;Basic<br />\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;Cooperative<br />\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;Interdependent<br />\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;Disintegrating</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	DAY TWO<br />\r\n	Inter-relational Causes of Uncoupling<br />\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;A change in key personnel<br />\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;Breach of Trust<br />\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;Cultural Mismatch<br />\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;Quality Problems<br />\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;External Causes of<br />\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;Subjective Attitudes<br />\r\n	Seeing Through Your Customer<br />\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;Pareto Analysis<br />\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;Determining Top Customers<br />\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;Customer Attractiveness<br />\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;Valuing Key Customer Accounts<br />\r\n	Key account risk:<br />\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;Customer&rsquo;s Business Situation<br />\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;Internal value chain<br />\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;Customer&rsquo;s View of your Company<br />\r\n	Key Account Buying Process Analysis<br />\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;Key dimensions of Buyer Behaviour<br />\r\n	DAY THREE<br />\r\n	Who buys?<br />\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;The buying centre<br />\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;Roles of Sponsor<br />\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;Strategic Coach<br />\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;Antisponsor<br />\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;The Buy-Sell Heirarchy<br />\r\n	Key strategic issues for pricing, sales, and the firm&rsquo;s profits:<br />\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;Price Contagion Management<br />\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;Account Management Incentive Alignment:<br />\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;Mutually Beneficial Value Alignment:<br />\r\n	Team Approach &amp; Composition<br />\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;Key Account Manager<br />\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;Account Team Member<br />\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;Extended Team Member<br />\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;Account Review Committee<br />\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;Personality types<br />\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;Motivation balance<br />\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;Managing groups<br />\r\n	Skills Requirements for Key Account Managers<br />\r\n	Setting and Implementing Strategies on Key Accounts<br />\r\n	Charter Statement<br />\r\n	Elements most critical<br />\r\n	&bull;&nbsp;Setting Strategies SWOT Analysis<br />\r\n	&bull;&nb